.TH NET-DIAG 1 "2026-05-13" "net-mgr" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
net-diag \- print everything net-mgr knows about a host
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B net-diag
.RI [ options ]
.IR name-regex | IP
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B net-diag
is a one-stop diagnostic dump for a host: how it's connected (which
interfaces, AP association, vendor/kind), where each address came
from (the
.B addresses.source
field, e.g.
.IR wndrhawk:DHCP ", " kc-qernel:dhcp.master ", " 192.168.15.231:arp ),
DHCP lease records, the names net-mgr knows it by, the open-port
inventory, and a fresh DNS view (forward + reverse) from the
caller's resolver.
.PP
The argument is treated as an IP if it parses as v4 or v6, else as
a Perl regex anchored to the full name and matched against
.BR machines.primary_name ", " hostnames ", " aliases ", and "
.BR friendly_names .
Multiple matches are printed in turn, so
.B 'nas3.*'
prints
.IR nas3-up ", " nas3-down ", " nas3-dwn2
in one go.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\fB\-\-listen \fIHOST:PORT\fR
net-mgr daemon to query (default
.BR 127.0.0.1:7531 ).
.TP
.B \-\-no\-dns
Skip the local-resolver DNS lookups entirely.
.TP
.B \-\-no\-rdns
Skip just reverse DNS; forward lookups still run.
.TP
.B \-\-raw
Don't pretty-translate
.IR <ip>:<method>
source fields to
.IR <hostname>:<method> .
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Show usage.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
At least one machine matched.
.TP
.B 1
No match.
.TP
.B 2
Bad arguments.
.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
Dump everything for nas3-up:
.RS 4
.nf
.B net-diag nas3-up
.fi
.RE
.PP
Same, by IP:
.RS 4
.nf
.B net-diag 192.168.15.104
.fi
.RE
.PP
Show every nas3 sibling at once:
.RS 4
.nf
.B net-diag 'nas3.*'
.fi
.RE
.PP
Skip DNS lookups (faster, useful when off-network):
.RS 4
.nf
.B net-diag --no-dns zmc1
.fi
.RE
.SH "SEE ALSO"
.BR net-lookup (1),
.BR net-show (1),
.BR net-find-rogue-dhcp (1),
.BR net-mgr (7)
